(25, 0, 'Lamentations', 'Lam', 5, null, 25, 1, 0, 0, 0, 0, 'Lam', '~lamentations~la~lam~lament~', null, null, '<p>Although the writer of Lamentations is not known for certain, there is good evidence that Jeremiah was the writer and conservative scholars have defended that position. The Septuagint and the Latin Vulgate (which was in large part a translation of the Septuagint) have a preface to Lamentation that the Masoretic Hebrew text does not have. The NET Bible translates Greek text as &ldquo;And it came to pass after Israel had been taken captive and Jerusalem had been laid waste, Jeremiah sat weeping and lamented this lament over Jerusalem&hellip;.&rdquo; (NET Bible text note). The NET note goes on, &ldquo;Scholars generally view the preface in the LXX and Vulgate as a later addition, though the style is Hebrew rather than Greek.&rdquo; But whether this introduction was original or by a later editor, it does show that centuries before the time of Christ, the scholarly Jews attributed Lamentations to the prophet Jeremiah, and evidence in the text supports that conclusion. For the purpose of this commentary, it will be assumed that Jeremiah penned Lamentations.[fn]</p> <p>Jeremiah was a prophet of God, and a writing prophet as well; he lived at the right time period to compose the lament, i.e., through the attack on Jerusalem, and its destruction by the Babylonians. Furthermore, he personally experienced the successive waves of the Babylonian rulers carrying Judeans captive to Babylon; and he experienced personal tragedy during this whole period, including imprisonment and torture.</p> <p>Lamentations is very poetic and very carefully structured. Of the five chapters of Lamentations, each chapter is an acrostic; that is each line starts with a different letter of the Hebrew alphabet. Chapters 1, 2, and 4 start with the word <em>aycha</em>, which starts with an aleph, the first letter in the Hebrew alphabet and equivalent to our letter &ldquo;A&rdquo; (chapters 3 and 5 start with a different Hebrew word, but both chapters start with an aleph, Then, for each letter of the Hebrew alphabet, there is one verse. However, chapter three is also an alphabetical acrostic, but each letter has three verses. So Lamentations chapters 1, 2, 4, and 5 have 22 verses while Lamentations chapter 3 has 66 verses. That would lead us to think that chapter three is three times as long as chapters 1, 2, 4, and 5, but that is not the case. The verses in chapter three are much shorter than the verses in the other chapters; the occurrence of the acrostic letters occurs more often. So while on the surface chapter 3 seems to be much longer than the other chapters, actually reading it shows that it is about the same length.</p> <p>The book of Lamentations is an elegy (not to be confused with eulogy). An elegy is a poem of deep reflection, typically a lament for the dead. The first elegy in the Bible is David&rsquo;s lament over the death of Saul and his beloved friend Jonathan (2 Sam. 1:17-27). The writer of Lamentations, likely Jeremiah, seems to be an eyewitness of what he writes about because the whole elegy is written with intense and emotional language that would seem to come from personal experience and personal feelings.</p> <p>Both the books of Jeremiah and Lamentations reveal the deep feelings the writer had for Judah and Jerusalem. He writes in an intimate, tender, and even sad way, calling her the &ldquo;virgin daughter&rdquo; (Jer. 14:17; Lam. 1:15) and referring to her as a &ldquo;daughter&rdquo; many times, note especially &ldquo;Daughter Zion&rdquo; (Jer. 4:31; 6:2, 23; Lam. 1:6; 2:1,4, 8, 10, 13), &ldquo;Daughter Judah&rdquo; (Lam. 1:15; 2:2, 5), and &ldquo;Daughter Jerusalem&rdquo; (Lam. 2:13, 15; 4:22). The figurative use of &ldquo;daughter&rdquo; portrays Judah and Jerusalem as a very young woman, beloved but inexperienced and vulnerable, but at the same time the writer does not hesitate to put the blame for her tragic circumstances on her ungodly behavior and defiance of God. The bereavement of &ldquo;Daughter Jerusalem&rdquo; is also a tragedy because in a very real sense daughters were the strength of the future kingdom because only they could bear the children that would keep the society alive and strong. Judah&rsquo;s sin has brought disaster, and there is terror on every side (Jer. 6:25; 46:5; Lam. 2:22). But the writer also notes that priests and prophets have led the people astray, although he notes that the people willingly follow that ungodly lead (Jer. 5:31; 14:13-14; Lam. 2:14).</p> <p>The ability of Lamentations to get the reader in touch with the deep emotions we feel, especially in times of disaster. has led to the common practice among Jews to read the book of Lamentations in their synagogues on the ninth day of the month Av, the day and month the Temple was burned by Nebuchadnezzar.</p>'),
