(29, 0, 'Joel', 'Joel', 3, null, 29, 1, 0, 0, 0, 0, 'Joe', '~joel~joe~jl~', null, null, '<p>Joel was a prophet in Jerusalem, and the major subject of the book of Joel is the Day of the LORD, the Day of Yahweh, most specifically the Great Tribulation.</p> <p>The date Joel was written is hotly debated. Many liberal scholars place it after the exile, but it could have been, and likely was, written before the Babylonian destruction of Jerusalem. Thankfully, knowing the date Joel was written does not severely influence the text since it does deal to such an extent with the Day of Yahweh, which is still future.</p>'),
(29, 4, 'Doulos', '-', 1, null, 29, 0, 0, 0, 0, 2, '-', null, null, null, null),
(30, 0, 'Amos', 'Amos', 9, null, 30, 1, 0, 0, 0, 0, 'Amo', '~amos~am~amo~', null, null, '<p>Amos was a prophet who lived during the reigns of Uzziah, king of Judah (799-748 BC; other scholars say 792-740), and Jeroboam (Jeroboam II) of Israel (801-762 BC; others say 793-753). Amos was from the kingdom of Judah, but his message was primarily directed at the northern kingdom of Israel. Nothing is known about Amos personally except that which is in the book of Amos. He was a shepherd from Tekoa (Amos 1:1), a town in Judah about 5 miles almost due south of Bethlehem. In Amos 7:14-15, Amos states that he was not a prophet, but says, &ldquo;I was a herdsman, and a farmer of sycamore figs&rdquo; (Amos 7:14). What Amos meant by saying he was not a prophet was that he was not a professional prophet or part of a prophetic guild or school, but was personally called by God for prophetic ministry.</p> <p>It is noteworthy that Amos said he was a farmer of sycamore figs, because the sycamore fig tree does not grow in the area of Tekoa, but in the lowland, so it is possible that Amos agreed to take care of someone else&rsquo;s trees in return for grazing rights, or it is also possible that Amos was wealthy enough to own land where he grew the sycamore figs. The wide range of knowledge and vocabulary in Amos shows that he was not just a poor ignorant farmer but was educated and experienced.</p> <p>That Amos lived during the reigns of Uzziah, who reigned 52 years (2 Chron. 26:3) and Jeroboam II, who reigned 41 years (2 Kings 14:23) gives us a basic time frame in which Amos lived. Also, in Amos 7:17, Amos predicts that Amaziah, a priest in Bethel, would be carried captive to an unclean land, his wife would have to prostitute herself to live, and his sons and daughters would die by the sword. Those events would have occurred in and after 722 BC when Assyria conquered Samaria and carried Israel captive to Assyria. All the datable events in Amos lead to a suggested date for his ministry somewhere in the area of 765-750 BC.</p> <p>The early years of the eighth century BC brought hope and prosperity to both the kingdoms of Israel and Judah. The Assyrians captured Syria around 800 BC and thus brought that ancient enemy of Israel to an end, but Assyria itself suffered internal struggles and was unable to pressure Israel and Judah, and to the south, Egypt had problems as well. At that time, two powerful and brilliant military leaders arose as kings: Jeroboam II in Israel and Azariah (also called Uzziah) in Judah. Their long reigns allowed for a period of stability and prosperity in Judah and Israel that had not been seen since Solomon and Israel in particular conquered territory in the north. At the same time, however, the blessings of prosperity brought increasing moral decay, and especially for Israel, prophetic warnings that Israel would be destroyed, which came to pass in 722 BC.</p> <p>During that time, Israel went further and further away from Yahweh and followed Baal and other pagan gods. The cult of Baal was heavily involved in ritual sex, which was directly opposed to the holiness in God&rsquo;s law and also destroyed family bonds. Also, pagan gods were generally capricious and violent, and that affected society as well. Reading Amos and the other prophets of that time shows a growing disparity between the rich and the poor, and a lack of concern on the part of the rich for the welfare of the poor, in fact, many rich people preyed on the poor to enrich themselves. God&rsquo;s concern for the poor and disadvantaged, which is so prominent in the Mosaic Law, was not part of the pagan religions, and that was certainly reflected in Israel and Judah as they became more and more pagan.</p> <p>God&rsquo;s love for His people can be seen in the fact that matching the moral decay going on in Israel and Judah were God&rsquo;s attempts to call the people back to Himself, because He raised up bold and powerful writing prophets at that time: Amos, Isaiah, Hosea, and Micah. Also, there were other prophets at that time as well who did not write about Israel and Judah, such as Jonah. Sadly, both Israel and Judah ignored the warnings of the prophets, and both kingdoms were destroyed, Israel first in 722 BC, then Judah later in 586 BC. However, not everyone ignored the Law and the warnings of the prophets. The personal example and powerful words of the prophets encouraged a small but committed number of people to walk in obedience to God and hope for the better times in the future that the prophets spoke about, but no one expected that those better times would still be future today, more than 2,700 years after Amos wrote. So believers today, just as believers back then, wait patiently in trust and hope for the prophecies of a wonderful future to come to pass.</p>'),
(30, 3, 'Bibliography', '-', 1, 'Bibliography (old)', 99, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, '-', null, null, null, null),
(30, 4, 'Asterismos', '-', 1, null, 30, 1, 0, 0, 0, 3, '-', null, null, null, null),
(31, 0, 'Obadiah', 'Obad', 1, null, 31, 1, 0, 0, 0, 0, 'Oba', '~obadiah~ob~oba~obd~obdh~obad~', null, null, '<p>&ldquo;Obadiah&rdquo; means &ldquo;One who serves [or worships] God,&rdquo; and it is a fairly common name in the Bible occurring some 18 times in various forms. Nothing is known about the Obadiah who penned the book of Obadiah except that he was a prophet called by God. Some Christian tradition identifies the prophet Obadiah with the Obadiah of Elijah&rsquo;s time who hid the prophets in a cave, but that is just tradition and is almost certainly too early for the two Obadiahs to be the same. Obadiah the prophet lived much later than Elijah.</p> <p>The date of Obadiah is not given in the book of Obadiah and so even conservative scholars differ, and suggested dates range from the ninth to sixth century BC. However, the content of the book argues strongly for a date for what was written in the book soon after the destruction of Jerusalem by Babylon in 586 BC. However, it is likely that Obadiah wrote later than that, and thus wrote about events that happened earlier. But even so, it does not seem like he would have written much later than the events he describes in the book, thus sometime between 586 and 500 BC.</p> <p>Although the date of Obadiah&rsquo;s prophecy is debated, the message is the same no matter what the exact background. Edom, which was often representative of all enemy nations, was against God and His people, and even though God&rsquo;s enemies persecute God&rsquo;s people and inflict terrible harm upon them, the Day of Yahweh is coming in which the enemies of God will be destroyed and God&rsquo;s people will be vindicated and established back in the Promised Land. The overall prophetic message that God&rsquo;s enemies will be destroyed and God&rsquo;s people vindicated occurs in a number of the prophetic books, although many prophecies do not speak of the whole picture, but give only a piece of what is coming (cp. Isa. 11:12-14; 34:1-5; Jer. 25:15-38; 49:7-22; Lam. 4:21; Ezek. 25:12-14; 35:1-36:38; Joel 3:19-21; Amos 1:11-12; 9:11-12).</p> <p>Although Obadiah wrote &ldquo;concerning Edom&rdquo; (Obad. 1:1), he wrote to the people of Judah and Jerusalem, The central theme in Obadiah is the destruction of Edom, a &ldquo;type&rdquo; of all of God&rsquo;s enemies, and the restoration of God&rsquo;s people in the future, in the Day of Yahweh.</p>'),
(31, 4, 'Pistis', '-', 1, null, 31, 0, 0, 0, 0, 2, '-', null, null, null, null),
(32, 0, 'Jonah', 'Jonah', 4, null, 32, 1, 0, 0, 0, 0, 'Jon', '~jonah~jh~jon~jnh~', null, '~~', null),
