INSERT INTO `book` (`book`, `testament`, `title`, `abbr`, `chapters`, `tagline`, `sqn`, `active`, `outlinepublished`, `outlinefinalized`, `bookfinalized`, `wscatid`, `bwabbr`, `aliases`, `metadesc`, `comfootnotes`, `commentary`) VALUES
(38, 0, 'Zechariah', 'Zech', 14, null, 38, 1, 0, 0, 0, 0, 'Zec', '~zechariah~zc~zech~zec~', null, '~~', '<p>Zechariah, whose name means &ldquo;Yahweh remembers,&rdquo; was a priest and prophet. He was born in Babylonia during the Babylonian Captivity, and returned to Judah under the leadership of Zerubbabel. His grandfather Iddo (Zech. 1:1) is named in Nehemiah 12:4 as one of the people who returned to Judah. Zechariah was a contemporary of Haggai (Ezra 5:1; 6:14), but continued his ministry long after him (Zech. 1:1; 7:1; Hag. 1:1; Neh. 12:1-16). Zechariah was young when his prophetic ministry started (Zech. 2:4).</p> <p>A major part of Zechariah&rsquo;s ministry was reproving and encouraging the people of Judah to be godly and also to rebuild the Temple of Yahweh (cp. Zech 1:1-6; 4:8-10). Also, however, Zechariah has wonderful prophecies about the coming Messiah. He foretold that the Messiah would be a man, and called him &ldquo;the man who is close to me [Yahweh]&rdquo; (Zech. 13:7), and &ldquo;the man whose name is &lsquo;the Branch&rdquo; (Zech. 6:12). Zechariah foretold the Messiah rule would be greater than just Judah, and said that he would &ldquo;branch out of his place,&rdquo; and also that he would build the Temple of Yahweh (Zech. 6:12-13: the Temple the Messiah will build is the Millennial Temple described in Ezekiel 40-44). Zechariah said nations would come to Jerusalem to worship and celebrate the feast of Tabernacles, and Yahweh&rsquo;s &ldquo;house&rdquo; (the Temple) will contain pots and decorations marked &ldquo;holy to Yahweh&rdquo; (Zech. 14:16-21). Zechariah also foretold that the Messiah would be both the king and the High Priest (Zech. 6:13). In fact, when the Messiah came to be king he would have a worldwide dominion (Zech. 9:9-10; 14:9, 16). Zechariah foretold that the Messiah would be struck with the sword of Yahweh and that his followers would be scattered (Zech. 13:7), and furthermore that his hands were wounded by his friends (Zech. 13:6), and he would be &ldquo;pierced&rdquo; (Zech. 12:10). Nevertheless, he would come and conquer the earth (Zech. 14:4). When the Messiah, God&rsquo;s servant the Branch, reigned as king there would be peace on earth (Zech. 3:8-10; 9:9-10). There is also an obscure prophecy that the Messiah would be sold for 30 pieces of silver (Zech. 11:12-13).</p> <p>Besides the prophecy of the Temple that the Messiah would build, there are many other end-time things Zechariah spoke about. For example, he spoke about the tribulation time before Christ conquers the earth when the nations of the earth would attack Israel (Zech. 12:1-3; 14:1-2). He also foretold that the Messiah would defeat those nations (Zech. 12:2-9; 14:3-4). He foretold some of the geographical changes that the world would go through when the Messiah ruled the earth (Zech. 14:4-5),</p>'),
