(56, 1, 'Titus', 'Titus', 3, 'The Epistle of Paul to Titus', 56, 1, 0, 0, 0, 0, 'Tit', '~titus~ti~tit~tt~ts~', null, null, '<p>As with all Scripture, Titus is &ldquo;God-breathed&rdquo; revelation (2 Tim. 3:16), and it was penned either directly by the apostle Paul or by an amanuensis, a secretary, who Paul was dictating to. As the name &ldquo;Titus&rdquo; suggests and Paul stated, Titus was a Roman of Greek nationality (Gal. 2:3), who was converted by Paul quite early in Paul&rsquo;s ministry (Tit. 1:4; Gal. 2:1). Titus was a faithful man and gifted leader, and he had traveled with Paul to Jerusalem early in Paul&rsquo;s ministry (Gal. 2:1-4). Also fairly early on, Titus went to Corinth to help with the work there, and so is mentioned in 2 Corinthians 2:12-13; 7:5-6; and 8:6.</p> <p>After completing three missionary journeys, Paul was imprisoned in Caesarea for two years (Acts 24:27), then traveled by ship to Rome (Acts 27:1-28:16), then was imprisoned in Rome for two more whole years (Acts 28:30; c. 60-62 AD). When he was finally released, Paul traveled again and at some point was joined by Titus, who accompanied him to Crete. The island of Crete is the fourth largest island in the Mediterranean Sea and was a Roman province. The population there was mainly farmers and fruit growers.</p> <p>There was so much work to be done to establish the church in Crete that Paul left Titus there to continue the work (Titus 1:5). However, Paul still felt he needed Titus with him in other places, so he planned to send a replacement for Titus and asked Titus to join him in Nicopolis (Tit. 3:12). Nicopolis, &ldquo;City of Victory,&rdquo; was a city in Epirus, a region in northwest Greece and a Roman province. Titus must have joined Paul there because by 2 Timothy, which Paul penned after he wrote the Epistle of Titus, Titus had traveled north into Dalmatia, which is in what is now Yugoslavia (2 Tim. 4:10). That Paul left Titus in Crete to continue the work shows the great trust that Paul had for Titus because the people in Crete would have been difficult to lead. Apparently, the people of Crete were so bad that they were proverbial in the Roman world for being liars, evil, lazy, and money-grubbing (Tit. 1:10-13). Thus the Cretans were Proverbial for being lazy liars in a similar way that the people of Corinth were proverbial for their sexual excesses.</p> <p>The Epistle of Titus does not tell us where Paul was when he penned Titus, although because he was on his way to Nicopolis and had decided to spend the winter there (Tit. 3:12), many scholars believe he was probably at Corinth. Also, the Bible does not explicitly say how the Epistle of Titus got to Titus on Crete, but it was likely carried there by Zenas and Apollos as they traveled through (Tit. 3:13). Paul penned Titus sometime after he was released from his first imprisonment but before his second imprisonment in Rome, at which time he wrote his last epistle, 2 Timothy, shortly after which he was executed. Thus Titus was written in the mid-60s AD (c. 65-66).</p> <p>Although the Epistle of Titus addresses many issues, two notable themes are the importance of leaders and their families to be people of sterling character (Tit. 1:5-9) and the necessity for believers to do what is good (Tit. 1:16; 2:7, 12-14; 3:1, 8, 14). Given the evil, lazy reputation of the people of Crete, having good character and living a good life would certainly set the Christians apart and also make the Good News about Jesus Christ attractive to others (cp. Tit. 2:10). Also, Titus has information about false teachers and divisive people and the harm they do to the Church, and thus the need for leaders who know and follow the truth and are of good character.</p>'),
(57, 1, 'Philemon', 'Phlm', 1, 'The Epistle of Paul to Philemon', 57, 1, 0, 0, 1, 0, 'Phm', '~philemon~pm~phile~philm~philem~phlm~pl~phm~', null, '~~', null),
(58, 1, 'Hebrews', 'Heb', 13, 'The Epistle to the Hebrews', 58, 1, 0, 0, 0, 0, 'Heb', '~hebrews~he~heb~hw~', null, null, null),
(59, 1, 'James', 'James', 5, 'The General Epistle of James', 59, 1, 0, 0, 0, 0, 'Jam', '~james~jm~jam~jas~ja~', null, null, null),
(60, 1, '1 Peter', '1 Pet', 5, 'The First General Epistle of Peter', 60, 1, 0, 0, 0, 0, '1Pe', '~1peter~1pe~1pet~1p~', null, null, null),
(61, 1, '2 Peter', '2 Pet', 3, 'The Second General Epistle of Peter', 61, 1, 0, 0, 1, 0, '2Pe', '~2peter~2pe~2pet~2p~', null, null, null),
(62, 1, '1 John', '1 John', 5, 'The First General Epistle of John', 62, 1, 0, 0, 0, 0, '1Jo', '~1john~1jo~1jn~1j~1joh~', null, null, '<p><strong>Author:</strong> The author of 1 John is the apostle John, John the son of Zebedee. The Church Fathers Irenaeus, Clement of Alexandria, Tertullian, and Origin all identified John as the author.</p> <p><strong>Date:</strong> The Epistles of John are difficult to date, but internal and external evidence suggests a date of between 85 and 95 AD.</p> <p><strong>Recipients:</strong> 1 John is written to Christians. &ldquo;I have written these things to you who believe in the name of the Son of God so that you can know that you have life <em>in the</em> age <em>to come</em>&rdquo; (1 John 5:13; cp. 1 John 2:12-14, 18; 3:1-2). The Epistle of 1 John covers the basic subjects of Christianity, including, Jesus&rsquo; death and sacrifice for sin (1 John 2:2; 3:5, 16; 4:10); his return (1 John 2:28; 3:2); salvation by believing in Jesus (1 John 5:1, 13); the New Birth (born again, born of God. 1 John 2:29; 3:1-2, 9; 5:4, 18); the use of &ldquo;in him,&rdquo; signifying being in union with Christ and part of the Body of Christ (1 John 5:20); the importance of fellowship with God, Christ, and other Christians (1 John 1:1-7); the coming judgment for Christians (1 John 2:28; 5:17), and the necessity of walking in love, which is a major theme of the epistle.</p> <p>The fact that the epistle does not specify any specific place or group to whom the epistle was sent suggests that this epistle was to be a circular and go to all Christians, and indeed, the message in it applies to all Christians.</p>'),
(63, 1, '2 John', '2 John', 1, 'The Second General Epistle of John', 63, 1, 0, 0, 0, 0, '2Jo', '~2john~2jo~2jn~2j~2joh~', null, null, null),
